# Detailed Report on the 2021 Chlorine Shortage: Causes and Implications

## Introduction

The year 2021 witnessed a significant shortage of chlorine, particularly affecting the swimming pool industry in the United States. This shortage led to soaring prices, supply constraints, and a scramble among pool owners and service providers to find alternatives. The shortage was not an isolated event but rather the result of a confluence of factors, including a catastrophic industrial accident, pandemic-driven demand surges, and supply chain disruptions. This report provides a comprehensive analysis of the causes behind the 2021 chlorine shortage, supported by data and expert insights, and offers an objective perspective on the broader implications for pool owners and related industries.

## Overview of Chlorine Use in Pools

Chlorine is a critical chemical for pool sanitation, primarily used to kill algae, bacteria, and other harmful microorganisms, thereby ensuring safe and clean swimming environments. Chlorine tablets, especially Trichlor tablets, are a popular form due to their slow-dissolving nature and ease of use. Approximately 70% of residential pools in the U.S. rely on Trichlor tablets for sanitation ([Sutherland, 2021](https://www.poolmagazine.com/news-insights/pool-maintenance-service/clearing-up-confusion-surrounding-the-2021-chlorine-shortage/)).

## Primary Causes of the 2021 Chlorine Shortage

### 1. The BioLab Chemical Plant Fire

The most immediate and impactful cause of the chlorine shortage was the destruction of the BioLab chemical plant in Westlake, Louisiana, in August 2020. The plant, one of the largest producers of Trichlor chlorine tablets in the U.S., suffered a massive fire triggered by Hurricane Laura. The fire burned for three days, releasing chlorine gas and destroying the facility's roof and inventory, including approximately 835 tons of chlorine tablets stored at the site ([Bomey & Golde, 2021](https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2021/06/29/chlorine-shortage-prices-jump-after-louisiana-factory-fire/7804893002/); [Underwood, 2021](https://www.cnbc.com/2021/05/03/why-theres-a-chlorine-shortage-in-2021-and-what-it-means.html)).

This incident removed a significant portion of the domestic chlorine tablet supply overnight, leaving only two other major domestic suppliers—Occidental Petroleum and Clearon Corp.—to meet national demand. The plant's reconstruction, expected to be completed by spring 2022, aims to increase production capacity by 30% ([Underwood, 2021](https://www.cnbc.com/2021/05/03/why-theres-a-chlorine-shortage-in-2021-and-what-it-means.html)).

### 2. Surge in Demand Due to the COVID-19 Pandemic

The COVID-19 pandemic dramatically increased demand for chlorine products across multiple sectors, including residential pools. With lockdowns and social distancing measures in place, many Americans invested in home swimming pools as a safe recreational option. Pool construction reached record highs, with approximately 96,000 pools built in 2020—a 23% increase over 2019—and an estimated 110,000 pools expected in 2021 ([Fazio, 2021](https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/29/business/chlorine-shortage-pools.html); [Bomey & Golde, 2021](https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2021/06/29/chlorine-shortage-prices-jump-after-louisiana-factory-fire/7804893002/)).

This surge in pool ownership and usage extended the pool season and increased chlorine consumption. Additionally, chlorine demand rose in other industries such as household cleaning, food processing, and manufacturing, further straining supply chains ([Orenda Technologies, 2022](https://orendatech.com/blog/the-chlorine-shortage-of-2021-how-to-adapt/)).

### 3. Supply Chain Disruptions and Manufacturing Constraints

The pandemic also disrupted manufacturing and logistics globally. Chemical plants operated with reduced staff and implemented safety protocols that slowed production lines. For example, manufacturers that typically staffed 12 workers per production line reduced to six, halving output capacity ([Sutherland, 2021](https://www.poolmagazine.com/news-insights/pool-maintenance-service/clearing-up-confusion-surrounding-the-2021-chlorine-shortage/)).

Shipping delays, port closures, and increased transportation costs compounded the problem, resulting in longer lead times and higher prices. Pool service companies reported wait times for chlorine products extending from the usual 7-10 days to 3-4 months ([Sutherland, 2021](https://www.poolmagazine.com/news-insights/pool-maintenance-service/clearing-up-confusion-surrounding-the-2021-chlorine-shortage/)).

### 4. Panic Buying and Stockpiling

The shortage narrative and media coverage led to panic buying among pool owners and service providers. Experts warned that hoarding chlorine tablets exacerbated scarcity, similar to toilet paper shortages early in the pandemic ([Bomey & Golde, 2021](https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2021/06/29/chlorine-shortage-prices-jump-after-louisiana-factory-fire/7804893002/); [Fazio, 2021](https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/29/business/chlorine-shortage-pools.html)).

Some consumers resorted to purchasing bleach from supermarkets to compensate, which is only half as strong as pool-grade chlorine and may contain harmful additives. This behavior risked creating secondary shortages and safety issues ([Bomey & Golde, 2021](https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2021/06/29/chlorine-shortage-prices-jump-after-louisiana-factory-fire/7804893002/)).

